<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1642,2016]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1436,152,796]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,227,1642,1668]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Stems</emphasis>
5.4(2.5–11.0) m long, 10.4(7.0–15.0) cm diameter, solitary. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[985,1075,1642,1668]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Leaves</emphasis>
15(12–20) per stem; sheaths 25.3(16.0–40.0) cm long; petioles 51.7(45.0–60.0) cm long; rachises 192.0(150.0–234.0) cm long, 16.3(7.8– 24.4) mm diameter; pinnae 12(8–13) per side of rachis; basal pinna 47.4(34.0–83.0) cm, long, 3.9(1.4–10.0) cm wide, forming an angle of 54(34–67)° with the rachis; apical pinna 42.9(34.0–54.0) cm long, 18.5(10.0– 25.5) cm wide, forming an angle of 25(18–29)° with the rachis. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[934,1116,1797,1823]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Inflorescences</emphasis>
branched 1 order, with an elongate peduncle, short rachis, and several rachillae, these pendulous at anthesis; prophylls and peduncular bracts woody, not covering rachillae at anthesis; prophylls 62.0 cm long; peduncular bracts 59.0 cm long, inserted 7.8(4.0–11.5) cm above the prophyll; peduncles 114.1(72.0–171.0) cm long, 10.1(6.3–12.5) mm diameter; rachilla 8(6–11), 50.8(33.0–64.0) cm long, 7.4(6.3–8.6) mm diameter; proximal lips of flower pits regularly shaped, rounded, not covering pits before anthesis, recurved; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[995,1064,1990,2016]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">fruits</emphasis>
compressed, obovoid in lateral view with an asymmetric base, ellipsoid in frontal view, with a pronounced longitudinal ridge on one side and several lesser ridges on opposite side, 17.0(16.2–18.0) mm long, 9.3(8.5–9.8) mm diameter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,152,796]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,504,229,255]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Distribution and habitat</emphasis>
. From 
<geoCoordinate box="[591,669,229,255]" degrees="3" direction="south" minutes="43" orientation="latitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" precision="925" value="-3.7166667">3°43S’</geoCoordinate>
– 
<geoCoordinate box="[687,773,229,255]" degrees="6" direction="north" minutes="45" orientation="latitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" precision="925" value="6.75">6°45’N</geoCoordinate>
and 76°02’– 
<geoCoordinate box="[925,1034,229,255]" degrees="79" direction="west" minutes="46" orientation="longitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" precision="925" value="-79.76667">79°46’W</geoCoordinate>
in western 
<collectingCountry box="[1171,1286,229,255]" name="Colombia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and western 
<collectingCountry box="[151,248,268,294]" name="Ecuador" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
at 854(300–1600) m elevation in lowland or montane rainforest (
<figureCitation box="[1016,1088,268,294]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[151,255,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,205,1234]" captionTargetId="figure-248@11.[148,1434,200,1259]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distribution maps of Pholidostachys amazonensis, P. dactyloides, P. occidentalis, and P. panamensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894918/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,152,796]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,417,306,332]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Borchsenius F. &amp; Borgtoft Pedersen, H. &amp; Balslev, H." box="[441,765,306,332]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 217" refId="ref10852" refString="Borchsenius F., Borgtoft Pedersen, H. &amp; Balslev, H. (1998) Manual of the palms of Ecuador. AAU Report 37: 1 - 217." type="book chapter" year="1998">
Borchsenius 
<emphasis box="[602,662,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. (1998)
</bibRefCitation>
were the first to point out the differences between populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1969" baseAuthorityName="Martius" box="[334,661,345,370]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="synanthera">
<emphasis box="[334,661,345,370]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Pholidostachys synanthera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from west and east of the Andes. The western population, here recognized at the specific level as 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Henderson" authorityYear="2012" box="[567,741,384,409]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis box="[567,741,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has inflorescences that are branched to 1 order and have elongate peduncles, short rachises, and several rachillae that are pendulous at anthesis (
<figureCitation box="[1209,1300,422,448]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,244,1981,2002]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,157,1960]" captionTargetId="figure-58@5.[140,1446,157,1962]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. A. Leaf blade of Pholidostachys occidentalis (Henderson 138). B. Inflorescence of P. occidentalis (Henderson 138). C. Inflorescence of P. dactyloides (Balslev 60677). D. Infructescence of P. panamensis (Henderson 3037)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894910" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894910/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) (versus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1969" baseAuthorityName="Martius" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="synanthera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. synanthera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with inflorescences that are branched 1–2 orders and have well-developed peduncles and rachises, and several rachillae that are spreading at anthesis). The fruits of the two species also differ. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Henderson" authorityYear="2012" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Pholidostachys occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has compressed fruits, obovoid in lateral view with an asymmetric base, ellipsoid in frontal view, with a pronounced longitudinal ridge on one side and several lesser ridges on the opposite side (
<figureCitation box="[1326,1423,577,603]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1097,1121]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1070]" captionTargetId="figure-318@8.[141,1445,169,1070]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. A. Fruits of Pholidostachys dactyloides (Dodson 14491). B. Fruits of P. occidentalis (Balslev 60678). C. Fruits of P. panamensis (Liesner 1255). D. Fruits of P. pulchra (de Nevers 4285). E. Fruits of P. sanluisensis (Juncosa 726). F. Fruits of P. synanthera subsp. synanthera (Couvreur 119). Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894916/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1969" baseAuthorityName="Martius" box="[151,470,616,641]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="synanthera">
<emphasis box="[151,470,616,641]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Pholidostachys synanthera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has scarcely compressed fruits that are ellipsoid with obscure longitudinal ridges (
<figureCitation box="[159,250,654,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1097,1121]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1070]" captionTargetId="figure-318@8.[141,1445,169,1070]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. A. Fruits of Pholidostachys dactyloides (Dodson 14491). B. Fruits of P. occidentalis (Balslev 60678). C. Fruits of P. panamensis (Liesner 1255). D. Fruits of P. pulchra (de Nevers 4285). E. Fruits of P. sanluisensis (Juncosa 726). F. Fruits of P. synanthera subsp. synanthera (Couvreur 119). Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4894916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4894916/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 4F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,152,796]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,469,693,719]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Subspecific variation</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Henderson" authorityYear="2012" box="[491,826,693,718]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis box="[491,826,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Pholidostachys occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in scattered localities from southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,251,732,758]" name="Ecuador" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
to northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[459,581,732,758]" name="Colombia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, but there are too few specimens to test for differences amongst these populations. Like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1967" box="[363,525,770,795]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Pholidostachys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dactyloides">
<emphasis box="[363,525,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. dactyloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this species has an unusually wide range in elevation.
</paragraph>
